[2] North Carolina: equine
Date: Mon 22 Aug 2011
Source: WITN.com [edited]
http://www.witn.com/home/headlines/Horse_Euthanized_After_Contracting_Mosquito-Borne_Disease_128184628.html


A 4-year-old horse in Halifax County had to be euthanized after
contracting the state's 1st reported case of eastern equine
encephalomyelitis this year [2011].

Triple E, as the disease is called, is a mosquito-borne disease. It's
preventable in horses by yearly vaccination, and experts are sounding
the alert.

"The number of reported EEE cases fluctuates each year," said State
Veterinarian David Marshall. "Late summer to early fall is peak
mosquito season in North Carolina, and this is right on schedule for
us to start seeing cases."

According to the state, "North Carolina had 6 reported EEE cases in
2010, 23 in 2009, and 13 in 2008. It is estimated that for every
reported case, 4 or more cases go unreported. There was one case last
year [2010] of West Nile virus, another mosquito-borne disease that
affects equines."

Officials report "people, horses, and birds can become infected from a
bite by a mosquito carrying the diseases, but there is no evidence
that horses can transmit the virus to other horses, birds, or people
through direct contact."

