[Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) has been known to affect horses and
humans, but also many birds. It has occasionally occurred in dogs, but
is rare.

There is a vaccine for horses. The vaccine is often combined with West
Nile virus. Horse owners should be vaccinating. Remember it takes at
least 2 weeks after vaccination to develop immunity. While protection
from EEE wanes in about 6 months, it is recommended that horse owners
vaccinate at least this often in areas prone to this disease.

The mosquito can transmit this disease to humans, birds, and rarely to
dogs. Animals cannot transmit the disease to humans.

Ridding your home, paddock, or other areas of any standing water can
help reduce the places where mosquitoes can breed. Water may be
standing in small areas, such as water in the overflow dish of a
flower pot, or inside an old tire. Eliminating these breeding places
can help reduce the prevalence of mosquitoes that carry the disease.
However, there are always complicated issues to communities spraying.
For some of the complications, readers are referred to ProMED-mail
posting 20110818.2504. - Mod.TG]
